Medicines for 2 pounds a day may reduce the risk of heart attack.
Thousands of patients who have had a heart attack may be expected to be treated with 2 pounds a day, as official representatives recommend that more people use it and for a longer period of time.
The anti-clotting medicine Ticagrelor reduces the risk of repeated heart attacks in people with heart diseases.
This medicine is already prescribed for 12 months after heart attack, reducing the risk of recurrent heart attack.
It is recommended to use NHS at 4 years after heart attack to further reduce the risk of heart attack in people with cardiovascular problems.
However, the current use of NHS-managed NICE is recommended for 4 years after heart attack to further reduce cardiovascular risk.
Each year, about 140,000 people in England experience a heart attack, and a quarter of them experience a heart attack or stroke.
Heart attack and stroke are caused by a build-up of fat in the walls of the heart, causing blockages.
If the blockage breaks, it can cause a blood clot, blocking the flow of blood to the heart and causing a heart attack.
On the other hand, if a blood clot separates from the wall of the blood vessels, it can get further into the bloodstream and block blood's access to the brain, causing a heart attack.
People who have had a heart attack are at greater risk of recurrent heart attack.
Ticagrelor, produced by AstraZeneca, UK and marketed under the name Brilique, reduces the risk of blood clots forming.
The new NICE guidelines published today recommend that people take 90 mg of Ticagrelor for 12 months and for another 3 years 60 mg twice a day with aspirin.
Professor Carol Longson, Director of NICE Health Technologies, explains: "Despite the availability of medicines to prevent heart attack, more than a quarter of people who have had a heart attack experience another heart attack or stroke, often with severe consequences."
Fear of repeated heart attack can have a negative impact on a person's quality of life.
Evidence suggests that Ticagrelor combined with aspirin effectively reduces the risk of recurrent heart attack and heart attack in people who have experienced it.
Preliminaryly recommending treatment with Ticagrelor, we are glad that we can extend treatment options to thousands of people who are thus benefiting.
In view of the limited information on the efficacy and safety of Ticagrelor, especially the risk of bleeding when used for more than three years, the draft guidelines do not recommend its use beyond this time limit.
