German researchers are discussing the number of victims of the Berlin Wall.
According to a new study, the number of deaths under the Communist yoke of the former East German border could be much higher than previously thought, but doubts about the actual number of victims have still not been dispelled.
According to data released on Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, on the border with the western allies and the later West Germany, the Communist authorities murdered 1,841 people trying to get out of their controlled territory.
The museum has been studying border-related deaths for years and periodically adjusting the number of victims.
This year, another 11 deaths have been added to the list, including among the victims a six-year-old boy who drowned in trying to get to West Germany through the then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
The new victims of the Berlin Wall also include the Soviet army deserters.
"The total amount of harm caused by the double evil of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented," says the museum director Aleksandrs Hildebrante.
"Our task is to make sure that the graves of those who died in an attempt to escape from a Communist-controlled country are maintained and not lost," stressed the Hildebrant's statement.
However, other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The number 1841 is inconclusive," says Jochen Schtate, an expert in the history of East Germany at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the newspaper SÃ¼ddeutsche Zeitung.
He, along with other researchers at the Free University of Berlin, is currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have only managed to confirm 260 cases.
In the past, researchers estimated that only the Communists at the Berlin Wall had murdered 138 people.
Taking into account those who died, trying to escape through the Baltic Sea or to get to the West through the territory of neighbouring countries, Stutta believes that the number of victims could reach about a thousand.
However, it is significantly less than 1841.
One of the reasons for the difference in the number of victims could be different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie Museum also lists all cases of suicide by East German border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also lists deaths that are not linked to direct violence.
"If seniors between 70 and 80 years of age died from a heart attack after the contraction of border control," Hildebrante believes.
However, Stutat is convinced that a distinction should be made between the elderly, who may have died as a result of the treatment they experienced, and those whose death was caused by a long waiting period during the hot weather on the bus at the border.
Regardless of this, the record of victims is not easy because the Communist authorities in East Germany did not collect such statistics, and researchers have to study documents in various scattered archives, states Statate.
However, the States Group has recently produced new documents and could therefore come up with a new estimate of the number of victims in the near future.
