In Spain, the failure to establish a government is a threat to the reduction of the deficit.
On 12 July a month ago, the European Commission (EC) issued its opinion that Spain and Portugal have not taken sufficient measures to bring the deficit level down to 3% of gross domestic product (GDP) required by the euro area.
It is estimated that despite the austerity measures implemented, Portugal's budget deficit was 4.4% of GDP at the end of last year and 5.1% in Spain.
The European Commission, however, decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries, while at the same time setting fiscal targets for the nearest time.
One of the reasons why the EC did not yet impose sanctions against these two countries is the increasing Euroscepticism in many countries of the European Union.
Additional sanctions would only increase this negative mood.
Critics point out, however, that the EC is not consistent in its decisions by agreeing on uniform rules from the outset and then unable to apply them in life.
Thus, for example, the President of the German Bundesbank, Jens Veidmann, pointed out that Europe is losing confidence in itself in this way, giving the people the impression that the European Union rules are recommendive, not binding.
The EC has now proposed and all Member States have approved an extension of the deadline for correcting the deficit to the end of this year for Portugal and for Spain by 2018.
The European Commission promises to examine the progress made by both countries in the coming months, while pointing out that both Spain and Portugal must be prepared to introduce additional austerity measures if circumstances so require.
The initial projections suggest that Portugal's target could be achieved in due course and the budget deficit could already fall to 2.5% of gross domestic product this year.
This means that, as part of the Stability Programme, this country's government must implement austerity measures of 0.25% of GDP this year.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with an additional focus on controlling the costs of purchasing goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complicated.
This year, the budget deficit should be brought down to 4.6%, next year to 3.1% and in 2018 to 2.2% of GDP.
In addition, in the next two years, consolidation measures should be at 0.5% of GDP each year.
