The Congress Chamber announces that military officials misrepresent reports on the Islamic State.
In a statement issued on Thursday, the Chamber of Congress states that representatives of the US Central Command have distorted the reports by depicting the war against the Islamic state in Iraq and Syria more optimistic than is actually the case.
The Central Command Intelligence Analysts express their general dissatisfaction with the provisional report of the task force established by the Armed Forces Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the representatives of the Republicans of the Defence Financing Sub-Committee, indicating that their leadership controlled the reports on American success in the fight against the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is the military base in Tampa, Florida, which oversees US military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
The latest news on this report reveals that the intelligence reports, confirmed by senior Centcom leaders, reflect the US's fight against terrorism more positively than is actually the case. The facts were regularly distorted, depicting better achievements than other intelligence analyses suggest.
Ken Kalvert, a representative of the Republics of California, says: "Centcom's behaviour is unacceptable - our soldiers are the ones who suffer when our policy makers receive false reports."
Centcom's management errors lie in the organisation's top management.
This 10-page report shows in detail the ongoing problems in the presentation and analysis of the Central Command of American efforts to prepare Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
Although it does not provide conclusive evidence that senior officials of Obama's administration have distorted reports, it shows that Centcom's leadership has put some pressure on analysts to display a more optimistic view of the threat posed by the Islamic state (also known as ISIS or ISIL).
The report indicates that in the first half of 2015 the central management press releases, statements and reports to Congress represented the situation in a significantly more positive light than was the case in reality.
For example, Centcom's representatives publicly announced that the recovery operation for Mosul could start already in April or May 2015.
Mosul is Iraq's second largest city, still under the Islamic State Control.
Mike Pompeo, a representative of the Kansas Republican Party, states in his report: 'More months of investigation is a clear indication of this'.
Between mid-2014 and mid-2015, key US Central Administration officials distorted the reports by depicting the ISIS threat in Iraq weaker than they were in fact.
The Republican Party set up a working group to learn that analysts are concerned that information about the Islamic state is being distorted.
As the investigation continues, the report published on Thursday will be followed by new findings in this case.
The General Inspector of the Ministry of Defence investigates the activities of the Centcom intelligence service.
Members of the Democratic Party of the Intelligence Management Committee published their own report on Thursday in which they agreed with some of the conclusions of the Republican Party Working Party.
In his report, the Democratic Representative Adams B. Shifs states that between 2014 and 2015, Centcom too restricted the preparation of intelligence assessments reports in relation to ISIS and the Iraqi Security Forces.
Mr Å ifs explains that this process "stopped the dissemination of information," worsened the ethics of analysts' work, and "dissemination of false facts'.
But Shif and the members of the Democratic Party added that there is no evidence that the White House has put pressure on Centcom analysts to produce reports according to the 'pre-determined or political position'.
The Daily Beast published the preliminary results of the congress investigation on Thursday.
In August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon General Inspector initiated investigations following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, the Pentagon representative, announced that the Pentagon would not comment on the congress report until the investigation continued.
He also added that experts sometimes interpret complex data differently, and the Ministry of Defence and the Intelligence Administration call for a constructive dialogue on vital national security issues.
The investigation is not limited to the question of whether the American-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is successful (an increasing number of representatives of the Ministry of Defence).
But last year's accusations call into question whether President Obama can fully rely on reports from Central Administration on military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan and other hotspots.
Criticism with regard to the intelligence of the Islamic State is reminiscent of events more than ten years ago when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker published a study saying that the administration of George W. Bush started the Afghan war, thinking too little about its possible consequences.
