Latvenergo follows the process of opening up the gas market also from the position of a potential trader.
The state energy company Latvenergo follows the process of opening up the gas market, both from the position of the consumer and a potential trader, said the company's press secretary Ivita Bidere.
"The decision whether or not Latvenergo will join the gas market as a trader in the future will be determined by the type of gas market model and regulatory framework to be established."
"Therefore, for our part, we are actively involved in drafting and commenting on regulatory enactments, as well as we submit our proposals," said Bidere.
The Agency BNS already wrote that the Ministry of Economics (EM) in cooperation with the Public Utilities Regulatory Commission and the energy company "Latvijas GÄze" has developed the Cabinet of Ministers Regulations project "Regulations for Trade in Natural Gas" that will change the existing principles of operation of natural gas market by ensuring the right to freely choose natural gas trader from 3 April 2017.
When working on the new regulation of the natural gas market, the EM aims to make the process of trading natural gas as simple and user-friendly as possible.
The most efficient and user-friendly service solution has therefore been chosen as the "market centre model', where all activities related to customer service are provided by a trader - one contract, one invoice and one information and customer service point, leaving the technical issues of the natural gas distribution system to the discretion of the distribution system operator.
A similar solution is currently being implemented for electricity trading.
We remind that the gradual opening of the market for household users is planned - even after 3 April 2017, those household users who do not want to choose another natural gas trader will be able to continue to receive natural gas from the existing trader at a regulated price, thus becoming related users.
"In this case, the obligation to supply natural gas to related users at a regulated price is imposed on the public trader', informed the Ministry.
On the other hand, economic operators will have to choose a natural gas trader with whom a natural gas trading agreement is to be concluded.
Pending the conclusion of a contract for the sale of natural gas, the existing natural gas trader will ensure the sale of natural gas for a certain period of time at a specified price.
The Cabinet of Ministers Regulations project specifies in detail the rights and obligations of natural gas trader, system operator and users.
The rules define the procedure for the delivery of natural gas to users and the interruption of its supply, the requirements for the safe use of the natural gas system, the rights and obligations of the trader, the public trader, the system operator, the user and the owner of the gasified facility for the supply and use of natural gas; the procedure for the settlement of the services received, the amount of interest for delay, the exchange of traders and the supply of customers in the event of disruption of natural gas supply; the procedure for the delivery of natural gas to related users by the public trader.
