NASA climate model: Venus once inhabitable planet
Based on NASA's latest climate models, Venus has once been a inhabitable planet.
Scientists at the NASA Godard Institute for Space Research have developed a model to explore Venus' history, using tools and algorithms that are also used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, whose surface is hot, where there is no water and the atmosphere of which consists almost exclusively of carbon, once had earthlike conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' slow rate of rotation can be explained by the dense atmosphere.
However, the latest simulations show that Venus once had a plan, a similar atmosphere to the Earth, and it turned slowly.
The model also looks at Venus' earlier topography.
There have been more dry areas on the planet than on earth, but there has been enough water and geographical diversity on the planet to create life and prevent the evaporation of water.
In the early days of Venus, the sun was 30 percent brighter.
In the GIS model simulation Venus spin model reveals that the light part of the day on it lasts 2 months, explained GIS scientist Antony Del Genio in a press release.
This process heats the planet's surface and causes rain, which in turn forms thick layers of clouds that act as an umbrella to protect the planet from the sun's heat.
This results in a moderate climate temperature that is actually a few degrees lower than the temperature on earth today.
The model represents Venus's history, which is similar to the theory of evolution developed by scientists in their hypotheses.
Although it was once inhabitable, over several billion years Venus has been exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet rays.
Its oceans evaporated, and the spirits were burned by ultraviolet rays.
As the water fully evaporated, only the thin carbon dioxide atmosphere with a deadly greenhouse gas - Venus, as we know it today - left behind.
Scientists published the results of the new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
