North Sea oil platform workers resume negotiations and postpone strike
The workers' strikes on the North Sea oil platform have been postponed because the two parties to the dispute have resumed the negotiations, and the negotiators have told them.
Periodically, strikes are organized against the oil processing company "Wood Group" on the North Sea oil platforms in which the company "Royal Dutch Shell" operates.
The joint statement states that the trade unions of the Wood Group and of the Unite and RMT have agreed to resume negotiations on the settlement of the dispute.
In the coming weeks, a series of full-day meetings are scheduled to start at the beginning of next week with the aim of re-examining the issues at stake.
The trade unions announced that their recent events, organised after a break of more than 25 years, were directed against the planned 30 per cent reduction in wages.
This year, due to negative market pressure, the Wood Group reduced wages for North Sea workers by 9 percent.
Already in 2014, the company reduced the wages of land workers by 10 percent.
The company explains that additional wage cuts would allow the company to survive the market downturn.
On the other hand, several thousands of people had already reduced their salaries and announced plans to cease oil and natural gas operations in 10 countries in order to optimise their work in preparation for a large-scale merger with the British energy company, the BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure due to falling oil prices, and the UK's decision to leave the European Union further complicates the situation.
At the beginning of the week, Scottish MEP Dave Anderson met with workers' representatives to discuss one of the most important issues - the North Sea strike plans.
He said that the North Sea is vital for the region's economy.
In his report, he explains that the North Sea and the country as a whole need an economy that benefits all, not individual individuals.
In 2016, nearly 1.4 billion dollars are expected to be invested in new North Sea projects, compared to 7 billion dollars invested over the last five years.
Kepler measures the rate of rotation of stars in the column constellation.
The latest mission of Kepler's telescope has helped astronomers to compile the most complete catalogue of the speed of the stars in the Plejade constellation.
The new data helps astronomers to understand why the stars in this constellation rotate at different speeds, as well as how the speed of the stars refers to the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other constellations, we will get more information on the relationship between the mass of stars, age and even the history of its solar system," said Pasadena Caltech Infrared Process and Analytical Center scientist Luisa Rebula.
The Plejade constellation is 445 light years away from Earth.
Many stars in this constellation only begin to grow, reaching about 125 million years of age.
They turn at maximum speed.
As they turn at maximum speed, these rising stars emit large amounts of star winds.
When the winds get into the magnetic field of the stars, they slow down the stars.
As stars age, their speed decreases.
Kepler measures the speed of each star by determining the time between the appearance of recognizable star areas, such as sun spots.
The latest star speed catalogue shows that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller stars.
Rebul compares stars to dancers, larger dancers perform piruets slower than small dancers.
Rebul tells that in the "ballet" of Plejade it can be seen that slowly rotating objects are larger and more solid, while faster rotating objects are very small stars.
Thanks to the fact that the Plejade constellation is so close, it serves as a great space laboratory, where you can compare star characteristics to spin speeds.
Rebuls tells us that the Plejade constellation helps to create theoretical models for star rotation in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when and why the speed of the stars slows down and about their complete stopping process.
Rebul and his colleagues presented a detailed analysis of the rotation speed of Plejade stars in three new publications, which will shortly be published in the Astronomy Journal.
